  *TL;DR.* We shrank the free-variable count of the V2RDM model by a factor
  of $2.6 times$ and made the model parse cleanly through Mosek's presolve.
  But on a $1$ TiB / $128$-core server, the run still ate $approx 675$ GiB
  of RAM and was killed before a single interior-point iteration. The
  bottleneck is no longer the number of free variables. It is the dense
  affine PSD cones $attach(Q, tl: 2)(D) succ.eq 0$ and
  $attach(G, tl: 2)(D) succ.eq 0$, which Mosek scalarizes into hundreds of
  thousands of affine conic rows. The next move is to drop those dense
  affine PSD blocks and impose them lazily as scalar eigenvector cuts.
]

= Original goal

Solve the periodic H#sub[4] V2RDM relaxation at $N_k = 2$ with the standard
PQG conditions
$
  attach(D, tl: 2) succ.eq 0, quad attach(Q, tl: 2) succ.eq 0, quad attach(G, tl: 2) succ.eq 0,
$
inside the NCTSSoS framework, using `MosekTools.jl` as the conic solver.
The ambient space has $M = 32$ spin-orbitals
($2$ momenta $times$ $2$ spins $times$ $8$ active orbitals) and $8$
electrons. Direct moment-/SOS-based relaxations of the full Hamiltonian are
out of reach; V2RDM is the small relaxation that should plausibly fit.

The earlier baseline was COSMO, which never even printed its banner on this
problem shape. So "make it work on Mosek" is a real engineering target,
not a microbenchmark.

= Step 1 #sym.dash.en D-only moment-basis formulation

We start with the most cone-frugal NCTSSoS formulation:
$
  B_D = {1} union {a_i a_j : i < j},
$
i.e. identity plus the $attach(D, tl: 2)$ pair-annihilator basis #emph[only].
No $attach(Q, tl: 2)$ basis, no $attach(G, tl: 2)$ basis. The reduced Hamiltonian
$attach(K, tl: 2)$ folds the one-body part into the two-body sector, so every
objective monomial is generated by $B_D$.

For 32 spin-orbitals, $binom(32, 2) = 496$ pair rows, plus identity:

#align(center)[
  #table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (left, right),
    stroke: 0.5pt + luma(180),
    inset: 6pt,
    [*Quantity*],                                        [*Count*],
    [Spin-orbital modes $M$],                            [$32$],
    [$attach(D, tl: 2)$ pair rows ($a_i a_j$, $i<j$)],         [$496$],
    [Moment basis size $|B_D|$],                         [$497$],
    [PSD block sizes (by pair momentum $K$)],            [$[256, 240, 1]$],
    [Unique moment-matrix entries],                      [$123\,137$],
    [Total symbolic basis size],                         [$138\,545$],
    [Zero scalar equalities (involution / Wick)],        [$1\,987$],
  )
]

The two large blocks $256$ and $240$ are the $K = 1$ and $K = 0$ sectors of
the pair-momentum decomposition. The $1$ is the identity block.

This is the cheapest the problem ever gets. It does not yet enforce
$attach(Q, tl: 2) succ.eq 0$ or $attach(G, tl: 2) succ.eq 0$.

= Step 2 #sym.dash.en Eliminated PQG formulation (no new variables)

The V2RDM trick: $attach(D, tl: 1)$, $attach(Q, tl: 2)$, $attach(G, tl: 2)$ are #emph[affine]
in $attach(D, tl: 2)$ via the standard fermionic anticommutation identities,
$
  attach(D, tl: 1)_(p s) = 1/(N - 1) sum_q attach(D, tl: 2)_(p q, s q),
$
plus the analogous Q/G constructors. So we keep $attach(D, tl: 2)$ as the only
free Hermitian variable and add $attach(Q, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) succ.eq 0$ and
$attach(G, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) succ.eq 0$ as #emph[affine] PSD constraints. No
new free variables, just new cones.

#align(center)[
  #table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (left, right),
    stroke: 0.5pt + luma(180),
    inset: 6pt,
    [*Quantity*],                                  [*Count*],
    [Free variable],                               [$attach(D, tl: 2)$ only],
    [Real variables ($240^2 + 256^2$)],            [$123\,136$],
    [$attach(D, tl: 2)$ blocks],                         [$[240, 256]$],
    [$attach(Q, tl: 2)$ blocks],                         [$[240, 256]$],
    [$attach(G, tl: 2)$ blocks],                         [$[512, 512]$],
    [Hermitian PSD blocks (D + Q + G)],            [$[240, 256, 240, 256, 512, 512]$],
    [Scalar equalities (sector + traces)],         [$5$],
    [JuMP constraint objects],                     [$11$],
  )
]

So compared with Step 1 we kept the same $123\,136$ free real variables,
but we now also enforce four extra dense affine Hermitian PSD cones (two
for $attach(Q, tl: 2)$, two for $attach(G, tl: 2)$). That is what V2RDM costs.

= Step 3 #sym.dash.en K-only vs spin-resolved comparison

The K-only blocking above lumps both spins into each pair-momentum sector.
The spin-resolved refinement splits each $K$-block by $2 S_z$ of the pair,
giving smaller but more numerous blocks. This is what the existing
benchmark helper `demos/H4PeriodicNativeV2RDMHelpers.jl` builds.

#align(center)[
  #table(
    columns: 3,
    align: (left, right, right),
    stroke: 0.5pt + luma(180),
    inset: 6pt,
    [*Quantity*],                              [*K-only*],                     [*Spin-resolved*],
    [Free real variables],                     [$123\,136$],                   [$47\,232$],
    [$attach(D, tl: 2)$ block sizes],                [$[240, 256]$],                 [$[56, 128, 56, 64, 128, 64]$],
    [$attach(Q, tl: 2)$ block sizes],                [$[240, 256]$],                 [$[56, 128, 56, 64, 128, 64]$],
    [$attach(G, tl: 2)$ block sizes],                [$[512, 512]$],                 [$[128, 256, 128, 128, 256, 128]$],
    [Hermitian PSD blocks (total)],            [$6$],                          [$18$],
    [Scalar equalities],                       [$5$],                          [$5$],
    [Mosek scalarized matrix vars],            [$approx 250\,000$],            [$94\,960$],
    [Mosek affine conic rows ($Q$ + $G$)],     [#sym.dash.en],                 [$489\,200$],
    [Total real-lift PSD rows (est.)],         [$1\,543\,136$],                [$584\,160$],
  )
]

The spin-resolved refinement removes about
$
  123\,136 \/ 47\,232 approx 2.61 times
$
of the free variables and roughly the same factor of solver-facing PSD rows.
That is the largest pure-structure win we have.

= Step 4 #sym.dash.en MosekTools / server experiment

We ran the spin-resolved eliminated PQG model against MosekTools on a large
shared server, after first verifying both local and remote license loads.

