Reference build cost (just for orientation): the JuMP-side build wall was
$approx$ $57$ s with $approx$ $212$ GiB transient allocations; Mosek's
printed presolve completed in $approx$ $0.04$ s. The expensive work that
ate the remaining hundreds of GiB was the interior-point setup #emph[after]
presolve, not the model build and not the printed presolve step.

= What is stopping us now

It is #emph[not] the number of free variables.

We already dropped from $123\,136$ (K-only) to $47\,232$ (spin-resolved)
without changing the math, and Mosek still ran out of a terabyte of RAM.

The bottleneck is the two #emph[dense affine] PSD cones
$
  attach(Q, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) succ.eq 0, quad attach(G, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) succ.eq 0.
$
Each entry of $attach(Q, tl: 2)$ and $attach(G, tl: 2)$ is an affine combination of
many $attach(D, tl: 2)$ entries. When MosekTools translates these into
solver-facing form, each Hermitian affine PSD block of size $n$ becomes
$O(n^2)$ affine conic rows, every one of which references many of the
underlying $attach(D, tl: 2)$ scalars. Concretely:

- Affine conic rows for $Q$ + $G$: #h(1em) $489\,200$.
- Scalarized matrix variables for $D$: #h(1em) $94\,960$.
- Total real-lift PSD rows: #h(1em) $584\,160$.

The Schur-complement and KKT factorizations Mosek's interior-point solver
builds on top of that affine map are what blow memory through the roof.
This is consistent with the MOSEK SDP scaling guidance: SDP cost is governed
by PSD cone sizes and affine conic rows, not by JuMP variable count.

So:

#align(center)[
  #table(
    columns: 2,
    align: (left, left),
    stroke: 0.5pt + luma(180),
    inset: 6pt,
    [*Lever pulled*],                                       [*Effect*],
    [Cut free variables ($123\,136 arrow.r 47\,232$)], [Helped, but not enough.],
