    [Eliminate $attach(D, tl: 1)$, $attach(Q, tl: 2)$, $attach(G, tl: 2)$ as affine in $attach(D, tl: 2)$], [Saves variables, not cone rows.],
    [Add $attach(Q, tl: 2) succ.eq 0$, $attach(G, tl: 2) succ.eq 0$ as dense affine PSD cones], [#text(fill: rgb("#a01f1f"))[Root cause of the OOM.]],
  )
]

= Recommended next direction: lazy Q / G eigenvector cuts

The clean way out is to stop materializing $attach(Q, tl: 2)(D) succ.eq 0$ and
$attach(G, tl: 2)(D) succ.eq 0$ as dense affine PSD constraints inside the JuMP
model, and instead enforce them by separation:

+ #strong[Solve the small model.] Keep $attach(D, tl: 2)$ as the only PSD
  variable. Drop the $attach(Q, tl: 2)$ and $attach(G, tl: 2)$ PSD cones. Keep the
  scalar trace and particle-number equalities.

+ #strong[Numerically check $attach(Q, tl: 2)$, $attach(G, tl: 2)$.] Reconstruct the
  numeric matrices $attach(Q, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)^star)$ and
  $attach(G, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)^star)$ from the current solution and compute their
  most-negative eigenvectors $v$.

+ #strong[Add scalar moment-inequality cuts.] For every violating
  eigenvector, add the linear cut
  $ v^dagger attach(Q, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) v >= 0, quad
    v^dagger attach(G, tl: 2)(attach(D, tl: 2)) v >= 0, $
  which is one #emph[scalar] inequality on the moments, not a PSD block.

+ #strong[Re-solve and repeat] until no eigenvalue of $attach(Q, tl: 2)$ or
  $attach(G, tl: 2)$ is more negative than a chosen tolerance.

What this trades:

- *Solver-facing rows:* down by orders of magnitude. We replace
  $approx$ $489\,200$ affine conic rows with a handful of scalar inequalities
  per outer iteration.
- *Outer iterations:* up. We pay in the number of separation rounds
  instead of in interior-point memory.
- *Convergence:* not guaranteed in one shot, but well-understood
  cutting-plane behavior; in practice few rounds suffice for V2RDM-shape
  problems.

If we want to stay #emph[inside] the NCTSSoS polynomial-optimization loop
rather than running a hand-rolled JuMP loop, we will need a small framework
extension: support for scalar moment inequality cuts of the form
$chevron.l p\, m chevron.r >= 0$ for an arbitrary polynomial $p$ in the
moments, without forcing those into a localizing-matrix PSD block. That
extension is much smaller than the cost of trying to fit dense affine
$Q$/$G$ PSD cones into Mosek for this problem size.

